{
  "title": "Refactoring Serverless Handlers using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide covers the process of modernizing serverless functions by leveraging FastAPI, a high-performance web framework for building APIs in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI provides automatic documentation, type hints, and robust performance improvements for RESTful APIs.",
    "Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+ allows you to write less code, reduce errors, and improve maintainability of your serverless functions.",
    "In this example, we will refactor an AWS Lambda function using FastAPI.",
    "FastAPI supports various web frameworks such as Sanic, Hypercorn, Uvicorn, and Aiohttp.",
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nimport fastapi\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException\napp = FastAPI()\n\ndef my_function(query_param: str):\n    return {'result': query_param}\n\n@app.get('/my-endpoint')\ndef get_my_data():\n    return my_function('Hello World!')\n``"
    },
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required to leverage the latest features and improvements offered by FastAPI.",
    "Ensure you have the latest version of FastAPI installed: `pip install fastapi[all]`",
    "It's also recommended to use an updated web server like Uvicorn or Hypercorn for better performance."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While FastAPI provides numerous benefits, it may not be suitable for all use cases and projects.",
    "There might be a learning curve when transitioning from traditional AWS Lambda handlers to FastAPI.",
    "Consider the complexity of your project before deciding to refactor using FastAPI."
  ]
}
